5000|$|Nonetheless, not all British {{science fiction}} from that period comports with <b>Stablefords</b> thesis. Some, for example, reveled in adventures {{in space and}} held an optimistic view of the future. By the 1930s, there were British authors (such as Eric Frank Russell) who were {{intentionally}} writing [...] "science fiction" [...] for American publication. At that point, British writers who used the term [...] "scientific romance" [...] did so either because they were unaware of science fiction or because they chose not {{to be associated with}} it.|$|R
